1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,837
You are walking down a sidewalk when a

2
00:00:02,837 --> 00:00:05,320
police officer stops you, turns you around,

3
00:00:05,320 --> 00:00:08,157
and runs his hands along the outside of

4
00:00:08,157 --> 00:00:08,866
your clothes.

5
00:00:08,866 --> 00:00:10,285
He has no warrant.

6
00:00:10,285 --> 00:00:13,122
He has not seen you commit a crime

7
00:00:13,122 --> 00:00:13,477
.

8
00:00:13,477 --> 00:00:15,604
Most people assume that is illegal.

9
00:00:15,604 --> 00:00:16,668
It is not.

10
00:00:16,668 --> 00:00:19,506
The rule that allows it was written in

11
00:00:19,506 --> 00:00:22,343
1968, and it began with one detective watching

12
00:00:22,343 --> 00:00:25,180
two men pace in front of a store

13
00:00:25,180 --> 00:00:25,889
window .

14
00:00:25,889 --> 00:00:28,726
This is the case that drew the line

15
00:00:28,726 --> 00:00:30,500
between a hunch and proof.

16
00:00:30,913 --> 00:00:33,770
We think of the Fourth Amendment as a

17
00:00:33,770 --> 00:00:36,270
simple wall: the police need a warrant,

18
00:00:36,270 --> 00:00:38,056
or at least solid evidence,

19
00:00:38,056 --> 00:00:39,841
before they can search you.

20
00:00:39,841 --> 00:00:41,627
For most of American history,

21
00:00:41,627 --> 00:00:43,413
that was close to true.

22
00:00:43,413 --> 00:00:46,270
But there is a gap in that wall,

23
00:00:46,270 --> 00:00:49,127
and almost every street stop in the country

24
00:00:49,127 --> 00:00:50,913
now passes through it .

25
00:00:50,913 --> 00:00:53,412
Over the next twelve minutes: the ordinary

26
00:00:53,412 --> 00:00:55,198
afternoon that created the gap,

27
00:00:55,198 --> 00:00:57,698
the standard the Supreme Court invented to

28
00:00:57,698 --> 00:01:00,555
fill it, and the quiet cost of letting

29
00:01:00,555 --> 00:01:03,412
suspicion — not proof — put a hand

30
00:01:03,412 --> 00:01:04,484
on your shoulder.

31
00:01:04,897 --> 00:01:07,861
It is October 1963, in downtown Cleveland,

32
00:01:07,861 --> 00:01:08,284
Ohio.

33
00:01:08,284 --> 00:01:10,401
A plainclothes detective named Martin

34
00:01:10,401 --> 00:01:12,942
McFadden, thirty-nine years on the force,

35
00:01:12,942 --> 00:01:16,329
is watching the street the way he has

36
00:01:16,329 --> 00:01:18,446
watched it for decades .

37
00:01:18,860 --> 00:01:20,495
He notices two men.

38
00:01:20,495 --> 00:01:22,539
One walks down the block,

39
00:01:22,539 --> 00:01:24,992
pauses at a particular store window,

40
00:01:24,992 --> 00:01:27,037
looks inside, and walks on.

41
00:01:27,037 --> 00:01:29,490
A short distance away he turns,

42
00:01:29,490 --> 00:01:32,760
comes back, and looks into the same window

43
00:01:32,760 --> 00:01:33,169
again.

44
00:01:33,169 --> 00:01:36,440
Then the second man does exactly the same

45
00:01:36,440 --> 00:01:36,849
thing.

46
00:01:36,849 --> 00:01:39,711
Back and forth, the two of them,

47
00:01:39,711 --> 00:01:42,981
about a dozen trips in all — five

48
00:01:42,981 --> 00:01:45,026
or six times apiece .

49
00:01:45,439 --> 00:01:47,713
To most people on the sidewalk,

50
00:01:47,713 --> 00:01:48,850
this is nothing.

51
00:01:48,850 --> 00:01:51,882
To McFadden, it is a pattern he recognizes.

52
00:01:51,882 --> 00:01:54,914
Men do not usually study a single store

53
00:01:54,914 --> 00:01:57,946
window a dozen times in the middle of

54
00:01:57,946 --> 00:01:58,704
the afternoon.

55
00:01:58,704 --> 00:02:01,736
He believes he is watching two men case

56
00:02:01,736 --> 00:02:04,010
a robbery — checking the layout,

57
00:02:04,010 --> 00:02:06,284
the register, the way out .

58
00:02:06,697 --> 00:02:08,958
He has not seen a crime.

59
00:02:08,958 --> 00:02:11,972
He cannot point to stolen goods or a

60
00:02:11,972 --> 00:02:13,479
weapon in plain view.

61
00:02:13,479 --> 00:02:16,493
What he has is experience and a strong

62
00:02:16,493 --> 00:02:16,870
suspicion.

63
00:02:16,870 --> 00:02:19,884
Under the ordinary rule, that is not enough

64
00:02:19,884 --> 00:02:21,014
to search anyone.

65
00:02:21,428 --> 00:02:23,311
McFadden approaches the men, identifies

66
00:02:23,311 --> 00:02:25,571
himself, and asks for their names.

67
00:02:25,571 --> 00:02:27,078
They mumble a reply.

68
00:02:27,078 --> 00:02:30,091
And now he has a decision to make.

69
00:02:30,091 --> 00:02:33,104
If these men are about to rob a

70
00:02:33,104 --> 00:02:36,117
store, at least one of them may be

71
00:02:36,117 --> 00:02:37,247
carrying a gun.

72
00:02:37,247 --> 00:02:40,261
If he is wrong, he is about to

73
00:02:40,261 --> 00:02:43,274
put his hands on innocent people for no

74
00:02:43,274 --> 00:02:44,027
legal reason.

75
00:02:44,441 --> 00:02:46,297
He spins one of the men,

76
00:02:46,297 --> 00:02:48,773
John Terry, around and pats the outside of

77
00:02:48,773 --> 00:02:49,392
his coat.

78
00:02:49,392 --> 00:02:51,558
He feels the shape of a pistol.

79
00:02:51,558 --> 00:02:53,724
He reaches in and takes it out.

80
00:02:53,724 --> 00:02:56,200
A second pistol comes off the other man

81
00:02:56,200 --> 00:02:56,509
.

82
00:02:56,922 --> 00:02:59,258
Terry is charged with carrying a concealed

83
00:02:59,258 --> 00:02:59,926
weapon .

84
00:02:59,926 --> 00:03:02,595
And his case exposes a problem the law

85
00:03:02,595 --> 00:03:04,931
had been avoiding for a long time.

86
00:03:05,344 --> 00:03:07,963
The Fourth Amendment protects people against

87
00:03:07,963 --> 00:03:10,582
"unreasonable searches and seizures." By 1963,

88
00:03:10,582 --> 00:03:14,073
the usual test for a search was demanding:

89
00:03:14,073 --> 00:03:17,565
an officer needed probable cause — a fair,

90
00:03:17,565 --> 00:03:20,620
fact-based belief that a specific crime had

91
00:03:20,620 --> 00:03:24,112
been committed — and often a warrant signed

92
00:03:24,112 --> 00:03:25,421
by a judge.

93
00:03:25,834 --> 00:03:28,107
Detective McFadden had none of that.

94
00:03:28,107 --> 00:03:30,759
He had not watched a robbery happen.

95
00:03:30,759 --> 00:03:33,789
He had watched two men look in a

96
00:03:33,789 --> 00:03:34,168
window.

97
00:03:34,168 --> 00:03:37,199
If the court measured his pat-down against the

98
00:03:37,199 --> 00:03:39,850
full probable-cause standard, the gun was an

99
00:03:39,850 --> 00:03:42,881
illegal search, and under the rule from our

100
00:03:42,881 --> 00:03:45,532
last episodes, the evidence would be thrown

101
00:03:45,532 --> 00:03:45,911
out.

102
00:03:46,325 --> 00:03:48,329
But push the other way,

103
00:03:48,329 --> 00:03:50,334
and a different danger appears.

104
00:03:50,334 --> 00:03:52,339
Police officers approach suspicious people

105
00:03:52,339 --> 00:03:55,546
every day, long before a crime is complete.

106
00:03:55,546 --> 00:03:58,753
If an officer can never check a person

107
00:03:58,753 --> 00:04:01,961
for a weapon until he already has proof

108
00:04:01,961 --> 00:04:05,168
of a crime, then the most dangerous moment

109
00:04:05,168 --> 00:04:07,975
of the job — the unknown person,

110
00:04:07,975 --> 00:04:11,182
the unseen gun — is also the moment

111
00:04:11,182 --> 00:04:13,588
the law leaves him most exposed.

112
00:04:14,001 --> 00:04:17,148
So the question that reached the Supreme Court

113
00:04:17,148 --> 00:04:18,722
was narrow and uncomfortable.

114
00:04:18,722 --> 00:04:21,869
Is there a kind of police contact that

115
00:04:21,869 --> 00:04:25,017
sits below a full arrest — a brief

116
00:04:25,017 --> 00:04:28,164
stop, a quick check for weapons — that

117
00:04:28,164 --> 00:04:30,918
the Constitution should allow on less than

118
00:04:30,918 --> 00:04:31,705
probable cause?

119
00:04:31,705 --> 00:04:34,852
Or does opening that door hand the police

120
00:04:34,852 --> 00:04:37,606
a tool they will use on anyone,

121
00:04:37,606 --> 00:04:39,179
for almost any reason?

122
00:04:39,593 --> 00:04:42,234
The Court understood both sides of that

123
00:04:42,234 --> 00:04:42,611
question.

124
00:04:42,611 --> 00:04:44,874
It knew the streets were real,

125
00:04:44,874 --> 00:04:47,892
and so was the temptation to abuse a

126
00:04:47,892 --> 00:04:48,647
softer rule.

127
00:04:48,647 --> 00:04:51,665
The decision it wrote in 1968 tried to

128
00:04:51,665 --> 00:04:53,551
hold both truths at once,

129
00:04:53,551 --> 00:04:56,569
and that is exactly why it has been

130
00:04:56,569 --> 00:04:58,078
argued about ever since.

131
00:04:58,492 --> 00:05:01,533
In 1968, by a vote of eight to

132
00:05:01,533 --> 00:05:04,574
one, the Supreme Court upheld the search .

133
00:05:04,574 --> 00:05:07,615
The opinion was written by Chief Justice Earl

134
00:05:07,615 --> 00:05:09,895
Warren — the same Court that,

135
00:05:09,895 --> 00:05:12,936
in these same years, was expanding the rights

136
00:05:12,936 --> 00:05:15,217
of suspects across the country .

137
00:05:15,217 --> 00:05:16,357
That detail matters.

138
00:05:16,357 --> 00:05:19,398
This was not a Court looking for ways

139
00:05:19,398 --> 00:05:20,918
to help the police.

140
00:05:20,918 --> 00:05:23,959
It was a Court that decided the street

141
00:05:23,959 --> 00:05:25,480
was a genuine exception.

142
00:05:25,893 --> 00:05:29,106
The Court built its answer in two parts.

143
00:05:29,106 --> 00:05:30,311
First, the stop.

144
00:05:30,311 --> 00:05:33,524
An officer may briefly stop a person when

145
00:05:33,524 --> 00:05:35,533
he can point to specific,

146
00:05:35,533 --> 00:05:37,942
describable facts that make him reasonably

147
00:05:37,942 --> 00:05:40,352
suspect that crime is afoot .

148
00:05:40,352 --> 00:05:43,566
Not a hunch he cannot explain — facts

149
00:05:43,566 --> 00:05:45,574
he can lay out later,

150
00:05:45,574 --> 00:05:48,787
the way McFadden could describe the pacing and

151
00:05:48,787 --> 00:05:49,590
the window.

152
00:05:50,004 --> 00:05:53,382
That phrase — specific and articulable facts —

153
00:05:53,382 --> 00:05:55,493
is doing quiet, heavy work.

154
00:05:55,493 --> 00:05:58,871
It means an officer cannot simply say a

155
00:05:58,871 --> 00:06:01,827
person looked suspicious and leave it there.

156
00:06:01,827 --> 00:06:05,205
He has to be able to name what

157
00:06:05,205 --> 00:06:08,583
he saw and explain why it added up.

158
00:06:08,583 --> 00:06:11,538
McFadden could: two men, the same window,

159
00:06:11,538 --> 00:06:14,494
a dozen trips, their heads together between

160
00:06:14,494 --> 00:06:15,339
each pass.

161
00:06:15,339 --> 00:06:18,294
Reasonable suspicion is not a feeling the

162
00:06:18,294 --> 00:06:21,672
officer has; it is a story he can

163
00:06:21,672 --> 00:06:23,784
tell afterward, in specific terms,

164
00:06:23,784 --> 00:06:26,317
that a judge can test .

165
00:06:26,730 --> 00:06:27,880
Second, the frisk.

166
00:06:27,880 --> 00:06:30,561
If, during that stop, the officer reasonably

167
00:06:30,561 --> 00:06:33,242
believes the person may be armed and

168
00:06:33,242 --> 00:06:36,306
dangerous, he may run his hands over the

169
00:06:36,306 --> 00:06:39,370
outer clothing — and only the outer clothing

170
00:06:39,370 --> 00:06:41,669
— to check for weapons .

171
00:06:41,669 --> 00:06:44,733
The purpose is narrow: not to find evidence,

172
00:06:44,733 --> 00:06:47,797
but to make sure no one gets shot

173
00:06:47,797 --> 00:06:48,946
during the encounter.

174
00:06:49,360 --> 00:06:51,839
And the Court drew that limit tightly.

175
00:06:51,839 --> 00:06:54,671
A frisk is not a license to empty

176
00:06:54,671 --> 00:06:55,380
your pockets.

177
00:06:55,380 --> 00:06:58,213
It is a pat-down of the outer clothing,

178
00:06:58,213 --> 00:07:01,046
feeling for the hard shape of a weapon

179
00:07:01,046 --> 00:07:02,108
— nothing more.

180
00:07:02,108 --> 00:07:03,879
If an officer goes further,

181
00:07:03,879 --> 00:07:06,712
reaching in to explore for something that is

182
00:07:06,712 --> 00:07:09,545
plainly not a weapon, he has crossed the

183
00:07:09,545 --> 00:07:12,378
line the Court drew and stepped back into

184
00:07:12,378 --> 00:07:15,211
the world that needs probable cause and a

185
00:07:15,211 --> 00:07:15,919
warrant .

186
00:07:15,919 --> 00:07:18,752
The whole point was to give an officer

187
00:07:18,752 --> 00:07:21,231
just enough, and not one inch more.

188
00:07:21,644 --> 00:07:24,882
The Court was honest about what this was.

189
00:07:24,882 --> 00:07:26,906
A stop is a seizure.

190
00:07:26,906 --> 00:07:29,334
A frisk is a search .

191
00:07:29,334 --> 00:07:31,358
It did not pretend otherwise.

192
00:07:31,358 --> 00:07:34,596
It simply held that this limited kind of

193
00:07:34,596 --> 00:07:37,834
search could be reasonable on a lower standard

194
00:07:37,834 --> 00:07:41,072
than probable cause — a new standard the

195
00:07:41,072 --> 00:07:43,501
law now calls reasonable suspicion .

196
00:07:43,501 --> 00:07:46,739
With that, the gun found on Terry was

197
00:07:46,739 --> 00:07:48,358
allowed to stand .

198
00:07:48,771 --> 00:07:50,931
One justice refused to go along.

199
00:07:50,931 --> 00:07:51,651
William O.

200
00:07:51,651 --> 00:07:54,530
Douglas warned that the Court was giving an

201
00:07:54,530 --> 00:07:57,410
officer on the street a power that even

202
00:07:57,410 --> 00:08:00,289
a judge did not have — the power

203
00:08:00,289 --> 00:08:03,169
to seize and search a person without probable

204
00:08:03,169 --> 00:08:03,529
cause.

205
00:08:03,529 --> 00:08:06,048
To loosen the rule below probable cause,

206
00:08:06,048 --> 00:08:08,928
he wrote, was a long step down a

207
00:08:08,928 --> 00:08:10,008
dangerous road .

208
00:08:10,008 --> 00:08:12,167
His was the single dissenting voice.

209
00:08:12,167 --> 00:08:15,047
But it would echo for the next half-century.

210
00:08:15,460 --> 00:08:18,636
The "Terry stop" became one of the most

211
00:08:18,636 --> 00:08:21,018
common encounters between police and the

212
00:08:21,018 --> 00:08:22,606
public in America .

213
00:08:22,606 --> 00:08:25,782
Every day, officers stop people on a standard

214
00:08:25,782 --> 00:08:28,957
that is real but blurry: facts that add

215
00:08:28,957 --> 00:08:30,545
up to reasonable suspicion.

216
00:08:30,959 --> 00:08:34,205
The strength of the rule is also its

217
00:08:34,205 --> 00:08:34,610
weakness.

218
00:08:34,610 --> 00:08:36,639
"Reasonable suspicion" depends on judgment,

219
00:08:36,639 --> 00:08:39,885
and judgment can be sharpened by training —

220
00:08:39,885 --> 00:08:41,508
or bent by bias.

221
00:08:41,508 --> 00:08:43,537
In the decades after Terry,

222
00:08:43,537 --> 00:08:46,377
some cities used the stop-and-frisk power so

223
00:08:46,377 --> 00:08:49,623
heavily that it became the center of a

224
00:08:49,623 --> 00:08:52,057
national argument about who gets stopped,

225
00:08:52,057 --> 00:08:54,492
and how often, and why .

226
00:08:54,905 --> 00:08:56,987
Picture how that plays out now.

227
00:08:56,987 --> 00:08:59,763
An officer does not need to watch you

228
00:08:59,763 --> 00:09:00,804
commit a crime.

229
00:09:00,804 --> 00:09:03,579
He needs a handful of facts he can

230
00:09:03,579 --> 00:09:06,355
later put into words — where you were,

231
00:09:06,355 --> 00:09:09,131
what you did, how it fit a pattern

232
00:09:09,131 --> 00:09:10,519
he has seen before.

233
00:09:10,519 --> 00:09:13,294
On a good day, that is careful police

234
00:09:13,294 --> 00:09:16,070
work stopping a real threat before it happens.

235
00:09:16,070 --> 00:09:18,846
On a bad day, the same low bar

236
00:09:18,846 --> 00:09:21,622
can make being stopped feel less like an

237
00:09:21,622 --> 00:09:23,704
event and more like weather .

238
00:09:24,117 --> 00:09:27,136
That argument is not really a disagreement

239
00:09:27,136 --> 00:09:28,861
about the 1968 ruling.

240
00:09:28,861 --> 00:09:30,586
The Court was careful.

241
00:09:30,586 --> 00:09:33,174
It demanded specific facts, not vague

242
00:09:33,174 --> 00:09:36,624
feelings, and it limited the frisk to a

243
00:09:36,624 --> 00:09:37,918
search for weapons.

244
00:09:37,918 --> 00:09:41,368
The problem is what happens when a careful

245
00:09:41,368 --> 00:09:44,387
rule meets the pressure of a quota,

246
00:09:44,387 --> 00:09:47,837
a bad assumption, or a long day on

247
00:09:47,837 --> 00:09:49,131
a hard street.

248
00:09:49,545 --> 00:09:52,616
And so Terry leaves us with a permanent

249
00:09:52,616 --> 00:09:53,000
tension.

250
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:56,072
We want officers to be able to protect

251
00:09:56,072 --> 00:09:59,144
themselves in the seconds before they know who

252
00:09:59,144 --> 00:10:00,680
they are dealing with.

253
00:10:00,680 --> 00:10:03,752
We also do not want suspicion alone to

254
00:10:03,752 --> 00:10:06,440
be enough to stop and handle anyone,

255
00:10:06,440 --> 00:10:06,824
anywhere.

256
00:10:06,824 --> 00:10:09,896
The line between those two things is thin,

257
00:10:09,896 --> 00:10:12,967
and it is redrawn on sidewalks every single

258
00:10:12,967 --> 00:10:13,351
day.

259
00:10:13,765 --> 00:10:14,474
Terry v.

260
00:10:14,474 --> 00:10:17,310
Ohio answered a question about the street: how

261
00:10:17,310 --> 00:10:20,147
much can the police do to your body,

262
00:10:20,147 --> 00:10:22,274
in public, on less than proof.

263
00:10:22,274 --> 00:10:24,047
The detective watched two men,

264
00:10:24,047 --> 00:10:26,884
named a real suspicion, and the Court let

265
00:10:26,884 --> 00:10:28,302
the gun stand .

266
00:10:28,715 --> 00:10:31,914
But almost everything in that case depended on

267
00:10:31,914 --> 00:10:35,112
being out in the open — on a

268
00:10:35,112 --> 00:10:37,111
man the officer could see,

269
00:10:37,111 --> 00:10:39,910
on a sidewalk anyone could walk down.

270
00:10:39,910 --> 00:10:42,309
The Fourth Amendment grew up protecting

271
00:10:42,309 --> 00:10:44,708
physical things: your house, your pockets,

272
00:10:44,708 --> 00:10:46,707
the ground you stand on.

273
00:10:47,121 --> 00:10:49,766
So what happens when the police do not

274
00:10:49,766 --> 00:10:51,750
want what is in your pockets,

275
00:10:51,750 --> 00:10:54,396
but what is on the device inside them?

276
00:10:54,396 --> 00:10:57,042
When the thing they reach for is the

277
00:10:57,042 --> 00:10:58,695
phone that holds your messages,

278
00:10:58,695 --> 00:11:00,349
